# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cyrillic-script
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The **Cyrillic script** (/sɪˈrɪlɪk/ ⓘ *sih-RI-lik*) is a writing system used for various languages across Eurasia.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] It is the designated national script in various Slavic, Turkic, Mongolic, Uralic, Caucasian and Iranic-speaking countries in Southeastern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Caucasus, Central Asia, North Asia, and East Asia, and used by many other minority languages.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] As of 2019, around 250 million people in Eurasia use Cyrillic as the official script for their national languages, with Russia accounting for about half of them.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] With the accession of Bulgaria to the European Union in 2007, Cyrillic became the third official script of the European Union, following the Latin and Greek alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Early Cyrillic alphabet was developed during the 9th century AD at the Preslav Literary School in the First Bulgarian Empire during the reign of Tsar Simeon I the Great, probably by the disciples of the two Byzantine brothers Cyril and Methodius, who had previously created the Glagolitic script.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Among them were Clement of Ohrid, Naum of Preslav, Constantine of Preslav, Joan Ekzarh, Chernorizets Hrabar, Angelar, Sava and other scholars.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The script is named in honor of Saint Cyril.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Since the script was conceived and popularised by the followers of Cyril and Methodius in Bulgaria, rather than by Cyril and Methodius themselves, its name denotes homage rather than authorship.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Cyrillic script was created during the First Bulgarian Empire.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] A number of prominent Bulgarian writers and scholars worked at the school, including Naum of Preslav until 893; Constantine of Preslav; Joan Ekzarh (also transcr.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] John the Exarch); and Chernorizets Hrabar, among others.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The school was also a center of translation, mostly of Byzantine authors.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Cyrillic script is derived from the Greek uncial script letters, augmented by ligatures and consonants from the older Glagolitic alphabet for sounds not found in Greek.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Glagolitic and Cyrillic were formalized by the Byzantine Saints Cyril and Methodius and their Bulgarian disciples, such as Saints Naum, Clement, Angelar, and Sava.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] They spread and taught Christianity in the whole of Bulgaria.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Paul Cubberley posits that although Cyril may have codified and expanded Glagolitic, it was his students in the First Bulgarian Empire under Tsar Simeon the Great that developed Cyrillic from the Greek letters in the 890s as a more suitable script for church books.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic spread among other Slavic peoples, as well as among non-Slavic Romanians.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The earliest datable Cyrillic inscriptions have been found in the area of Preslav, in the medieval city itself and at nearby Patleina Monastery, both in present-day Shumen Province, as well as in the Ravna Monastery and in the Varna Monastery.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The new script became the basis of alphabets used in various languages in Orthodox Church-dominated Eastern Europe, both Slavic and non-Slavic languages (such as Romanian, until the 1860s).
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] For centuries, Cyrillic was also used by Catholic and Muslim Slavs.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic and Glagolitic were used for the Church Slavonic language, especially the Old Church Slavonic variant.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Hence expressions such as "И is the tenth Cyrillic letter" typically refer to the order of the Church Slavonic alphabet; not every Cyrillic alphabet uses every letter available in the script.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Cyrillic script came to dominate Glagolitic in the 12th century.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The literature produced in Old Church Slavonic soon spread north from Bulgaria and became the lingua franca of the Balkans and Eastern Europe.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic in modern-day Bosnia is an extinct and disputed variant of the Cyrillic alphabet that originated in medieval period.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Paleographers consider the earliest features of script had likely begun to appear between the 10th or 11th century, with the Humac tablet to be the first such document using this type of script and is believed to date from this period.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] It was used continuously until the 18th century, with sporadic usage extending into the 20th century.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] With the orthographic reform of Saint Evtimiy of Tarnovo and other prominent representatives of the Tarnovo Literary School of the 14th and 15th centuries, such as Gregory Tsamblak and Constantine of Kostenets, the school influenced Russian, Serbian, Wallachian and Moldavian medieval culture.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] This is known in Russia as the second South-Slavic influence.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In 1708–10, the Cyrillic script used in Russia was heavily reformed by Peter the Great, who had recently returned from his Grand Embassy in Western Europe.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The new letterforms, called the Civil script, became closer to those of the Latin alphabet; several archaic letters were abolished and several new letters were introduced designed by Peter himself.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Letters became distinguished between upper and lower case.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] West European typography culture was also adopted.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The pre-reform letterforms, called *poluustav* (Russian: полуустав), were notably retained in Church Slavonic and are sometimes used in Russian even today, especially if one wants to give a text a 'Slavic' or 'archaic' feel.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The alphabet used for the modern Church Slavonic language in Eastern Orthodox and Eastern Catholic rites still resembles early Cyrillic.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] However, over the course of the following millennium, Cyrillic adapted to changes in spoken language, developed regional variations to suit the features of national languages, and was subjected to academic reform and political decrees.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Today, many languages in the Balkans, Eastern Europe, and northern Eurasia are written in Cyrillic alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic script spread throughout the East Slavic and some South Slavic territories, being adopted for writing local languages, such as Old East Slavic.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Its adaptation to local languages produced a number of Cyrillic alphabets, discussed below.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Capital and lowercase letters were not distinguished in old manuscripts.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Yeri (Ы) was originally a ligature of Yer and I (Ъ + І = Ы).
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Iotation was indicated by ligatures formed with the letter І: Ꙗ (not an ancestor of modern Ya, Я, which is derived from Ѧ), Ѥ, Ю (ligature of І and ОУ), Ѩ, Ѭ.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Sometimes different letters were used interchangeably, for example И = І = Ї, as were typographical variants like О = Ѻ.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] There were also commonly used ligatures like ѠТ = Ѿ.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The letters also had numeric values, based not on Cyrillic alphabetical order, but inherited from the letters' Greek ancestors.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Computer fonts for early Cyrillic alphabets are not routinely provided.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Many of the letterforms differ from those of modern Cyrillic, varied a great deal between manuscripts, and changed over time.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In accordance with Unicode policy, the standard does not include letterform variations or ligatures found in manuscript sources unless they can be shown to conform to the Unicode definition of a character: this aspect is the responsibility of the typeface designer.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Unicode 5.1 standard, released on 4 April 2008, greatly improved computer support for the early Cyrillic and the modern Church Slavonic language.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In Microsoft Windows, the Segoe UI user interface font is notable for having complete support for the archaic Cyrillic letters since Windows 8.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The development of Cyrillic letter forms passed directly from the medieval stage to the late Baroque, without a Renaissance phase as in Western Europe.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Late Medieval Cyrillic letters (categorized as vyaz' and still found on many icon inscriptions today) show a marked tendency to be very tall and narrow, with strokes often shared between adjacent letters.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Peter the Great, Tsar of Russia, mandated the use of westernized letter forms (ru) in the early 18th century.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Over time, these were largely adopted in the other languages that use the script.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The development of some Cyrillic computer fonts from Latin ones has also contributed to a visual Latinization of Cyrillic type.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic uppercase and lowercase letter forms are not as differentiated as in Latin typography.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Though both Latin and Cyrillic types feature letters whose upper- and lowercase forms differ more in size and proportion than in shape (such as Latin ⟨C c⟩, ⟨V v⟩, ⟨Z z⟩), these form a minority of the Latin alphabet but a majority of Cyrillic (particularly in upright rather than italic forms).
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Still, a good-quality Cyrillic typeface will include separate small-caps glyphs.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic typefaces, as well as Latin ones, have roman and italic forms (practically all popular modern computer fonts include parallel sets of Latin and Cyrillic letters, where many glyphs, uppercase as well as lowercase, are shared by both).
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] However, the native typeface terminology in most Slavic languages (for example, in Russian) does not use the words "roman" and "italic" in this sense.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Similarly to Latin typefaces, italic and cursive forms of many Cyrillic letters (typically lowercase; uppercase only for handwritten or stylish types) are very different from their upright roman types.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In certain cases, the correspondence between uppercase and lowercase glyphs does not coincide in Latin and Cyrillic types: for example, italic Cyrillic ⟨*т*⟩ is the lowercase counterpart of ⟨*Т*⟩ not of ⟨*М*⟩.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Note: in some typefaces or styles, ⟨*д*⟩, i.e. the lowercase italic Cyrillic ⟨д⟩, may look like Latin ⟨*g*⟩, and ⟨*т*⟩, i.e. lowercase italic Cyrillic ⟨т⟩, may look like small-capital italic ⟨T⟩.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In Standard Serbian, as well as in Macedonian, some italic and cursive letters are allowed to be different, to more closely resemble the handwritten letters.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The regular (upright) shapes are generally standardized in small caps form.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Notes: Depending on fonts available, the Serbian row may appear identical to the Russian row.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Unicode approximations are used in the *faux* row to ensure it can be rendered properly across all systems.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In the Bulgarian alphabet, many lowercase letterforms may more closely resemble the cursive forms on the one hand and Latin glyphs on the other hand, e.g. by having an ascender or descender or by using rounded arcs instead of sharp corners.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Sometimes, uppercase letters may have a different shape as well, e.g. more triangular, Д and Л, like Greek delta Δ and lambda Λ.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Notes: Depending on fonts available, the Bulgarian row may appear identical to the Russian row.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Unicode approximations are used in the *faux* row to ensure it can be rendered properly across all systems; in some cases, such as ж with *k*-like ascender, no such approximation exists.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Computer fonts typically default to the Central/Eastern, Russian letterforms, and require the use of OpenType Layout (OTL) features to display the Western, Bulgarian or Southern, Serbian/Macedonian forms.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] These solutions only enjoy partial support and may render with default glyphs in certain software configurations, and the reader may not see the same result as the author intended.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Cyrillic script has also been used for languages of Alaska, Slavic Europe (except for Western Slavic and Slovenian), the Caucasus, the languages of Idel-Ural, Siberia, and the Russian Far East.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The first alphabet derived from Cyrillic was Abur, used for the Komi language.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Other Cyrillic alphabets include the Molodtsov alphabet for the Komi language and various alphabets for Caucasian languages.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] A number of languages written in a Cyrillic alphabet have also been written in a Latin alphabet, such as Azerbaijani, Uzbek, Serbian, and Romanian (in the Moldavian SSR until 1989 and in the Danubian Principalities until the early 19th century).
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] After the disintegration of the Soviet Union in 1991, some of the former republics officially shifted from Cyrillic to Latin.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The transition is complete in most of Moldova (except the breakaway region of Transnistria, where Moldovan Cyrillic is official), Turkmenistan, and Azerbaijan.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Uzbekistan still uses both systems, and Kazakhstan transitioned from Cyrillic to Latin in 2025.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Russian government has mandated that Cyrillic must be used for all public communications in all federal subjects of Russia, to promote closer ties across the federation.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] This act was controversial for speakers of many Slavic languages; for others, such as Chechen and Ingush speakers, the law had political ramifications.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] For example, the separatist Chechen government mandated a Latin script which is still used by many Chechens.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Standard Serbian uses both the Cyrillic and Latin scripts.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Cyrillic is nominally the official script of Serbia's administration according to the Serbian constitution; however, the law does not regulate scripts in standard language, or standard language itself by any means.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] In practice the scripts are equal, with Latin being used more often in a less official capacity.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The Zhuang alphabet, used between the 1950s and 1980s in portions of the People's Republic of China, used a mixture of Latin, phonetic, numeral-based, and Cyrillic letters.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The non-Latin letters, including Cyrillic, were removed from the alphabet in 1982 and replaced with Latin letters that closely resembled the letters they replaced.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] There are various systems for romanization of Cyrillic text, including transliteration to convey Cyrillic spelling in Latin letters, and transcription to convey pronunciation.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] See also Romanization of Belarusian, Bulgarian, Kyrgyz, Russian, Macedonian and Ukrainian.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Representing other writing systems with Cyrillic letters is called Cyrillization.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The characters in the range U+0400 to U+045F are essentially the characters from ISO 8859-5 moved upward by 864 positions.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The characters in the range U+0460 to U+0489 are historic letters, no longer used.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] The characters in the range U+048A to U+052F are additional letters for various languages that are written with Cyrillic script.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Unicode as a general rule does not include accented Cyrillic letters.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] To indicate stressed or long vowels, combining diacritical marks can be used after the respective letter (for example, U+0301 ◌́ COMBINING ACUTE ACCENT: е́ у́ э́ etc.).
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Some languages, including Church Slavonic, are still not fully supported.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Unicode 5.1, released on 4 April 2008, introduces major changes to the Cyrillic blocks.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Revisions to the existing Cyrillic blocks, and the addition of Cyrillic Extended A (2DE0 ...
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] A69F), significantly improve support for the early Cyrillic alphabet, Abkhaz, Aleut, Chuvash, Kurdish, and Moksha.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Each language has its own standard keyboard layout, adopted from traditional national typewriters.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] With the flexibility of computer input methods, there are also transliterating or phonetic/homophonic keyboard layouts made for typists who are more familiar with other layouts, like the common English QWERTY keyboard.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] When practical Cyrillic keyboard layouts are unavailable, computer users sometimes use transliteration (translit) or look-alike (volapuk encoding) to type in languages that are normally written with the Cyrillic alphabet.
[src:cyrillic-script/cyrillic-script] Potentially, these proxy versions could be transformed programmatically into Cyrillic at a later date.
[src:cyrillic-script/бг] It has previously been rejected by ICANN twice, due to its visual similarity to Brazil's .br, but in 2014 an ICANN panel determined that .бг is not confusingly similar to ISO 3166-1 country codes.
[src:cyrillic-script/бг] The panel compared the two Cyrillic characters in several fonts to the Latin br, bt, bs, BT and BF.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] The call started on 19 November 2012 and ended on 3 December 2012.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] The Cyrillic domain proposal had to contain letters of the country's name.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] On 3 December, MarNet chose six proposals (.мкд, .мак, .македонија, .рмкд, .рм and .рмак).
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] In the second phase of the process, citizens voted for the final Macedonian Cyrillic domain.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] The winning proposal was officially announced in January 2013.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] This also relates to the .mk domain, which is also owned by MARnet.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] In the final phase of choosing the national Cyrillic domain, there were six domains.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] During the voting period, 2,288 votes were registered and the final results were announced on the official MARnet website.
[src:cyrillic-script/мкд] The domain .мкд was officially approved and registered on 20 March 2014.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain name **.рф** (abbreviation of Russian: **Р**осси́йская **Ф**едера́ция, romanized: ***R**ossíyskaya **F**ederátsiya*, ***.rf***) is the Cyrillic country code top-level domain for the Russian Federation, in the Domain Name System (DNS) of the Internet.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] In the Domain Name System it has the ASCII DNS name xn--p1ai.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain accepts only Cyrillic subdomain applications, and is the first Cyrillic implementation of the Internationalizing Domain Names in Applications (IDNA) system.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain became operational on 13 May 2010.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] As of 2014 it is the most used internationalized country code top-level domain, with around 900,000 domain names.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The Cyrillic letters рф stand for Российская Федерация, romanized as *Rossiyskaya Federatsiya*, lit.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain has an ASCII representation of `xn--p1ai` derived as Punycode for use in the Domain Name System.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain is intended for Internet resources with names in the Russian language using Cyrillic.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] As such, GNSO sought to avoid the direct transcription of "ru" into Cyrillic, "ру", and common abbreviations for *Russia* (Russian: Россия), such as "ро", in order to avoid confusion with the Latin ccTLDs .py (Paraguay) and .po (currently unassigned).
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] In English sources .рф can be romanized as .rf, but the latter is not a valid domain for Russia.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] Later, other countries have won approval of two or three letter Cyrillic ccTLDs such as .укр, .срб, .мон, .қаз, .бел, .мкд and .бг.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The preparation, development, and technical testing of the domain started in 2007 by registrar RU Center.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain delegation process started in November 2009 as an application to ICANN under the new Fast Track IDN ccTLD process.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The domain is expected to be launched in 2010.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] In preparation for a launch, RU Center opened a *sunrise* registration period for Russian trademark owners from 25 November 2009 to 25 March 2010.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] General public registrations are planned starting 20 April 2010 through June 2010 using a Dutch auction process, and at a fixed price beginning in July 2010.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] In January 2010 ICANN announced that the domain was one of the first four new non-Latin ccTLDs to have passed the Fast Track String Evaluation within the domain application process.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] In a press release in December 2007, Alexei Lesnikov of RU-Center suggested that an auction for domain names could be highly successful, as was the case with a similar domain name auction on the .su ccTLD.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] With comparisons being made with an equivalent Chinese TLD of .中国, it was anticipated that take-up of a Russian Cyrillic TLD could outstrip demand for the Latin alphabet equivalent, .ru.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] As of 2014 however, .ru has five times as many registrations as .рф.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The top-level domain became operational on the Internet on 13 May 2010.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The first two accessible sites were президент.рф (*president*) and правительство.рф (*government*).
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The traditional country code top-level domain (ccTLD) for Russia, based on the ISO country codes, is ru.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] There is no direct mapping of subdomains between рф and ru, they are independent domains hosting potentially different resources.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] However, many resources may use URL redirection or DNS pointers to provide mapping between the name spaces.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] For example, the URLs президент.рф (prezident) redirects to kremlin.ru, and яндекс.рф (Yandex) redirects to yandex.ru.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The second-level domain names are registered directly with user-defined names, such as company names.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] There are no standardized category names (such as com or org) used on the second level.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] The second-level domain names are only intended to have Cyrillic characters, but some have Latin characters, or digits instead.
[src:cyrillic-script/рф] For the third-level names, it is fairly common that "www" (Latin characters) are used, but most main company addresses do not use any third-level name.
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] The Serbian National Internet Domain Registry (RNIDS) has initiated on its forum (www.forum.rnids.rs) a public discussion on the Proposal of rules and processes for registering the Cyrillic domain ".срб".
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] The Proposal of rules and processes for registering the Cyrillic domain ".срб" is available on the forum of RNIDS.
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] The Rule book also determines the period for assigning the ".срб" domain according to the priority right, after which the period of free registration of the ".срб" domain will commence, based on the same or similar rules now applicable for the .rs domain.
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] ".срб" has, in many fonts, a very similar appearance to the Latin alphanumeric .cp6, which is not registered as a TLD.
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] Similarly proposed TLDs .бг (for Bulgaria) and .ελ (for the Greece) have been rejected or stalled because of this problem, but ".срб" has not.
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] The general policy for internationalized TLDs is to require at least one of the letters in a TLD to not resemble a Latin letter; 6 is a numeric digit (not a Latin letter) and is not used in any TLDs.
[src:cyrillic-script/срб] Furthermore, though б appears similar to a 6 in most Cyrillic alphabets, it does not in Serbian, where it more closely resembles Greek lowercase delta (δ), see the relevant section in the article on the letter б.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The domain name **.укр** (romanized as ***.ukr***; abbreviation of Ukrainian: Україна, romanized: ***Ukr**ayina*; Punycode `.xn--j1amh`) is an approved internationalized country code top-level domain (IDN ccTLD) for Ukraine.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] It is a common abbreviation used in Ukraine, as in *Ukrbank* and *Ukrnafta*.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] In June 2008 the ICANN approved a document that foresees the introduction of high-level domain names in Cyrillic and other national non-Latin alphabets.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] On 17 November 2009, Ukraine initiated an application to ICANN for assignment of the Cyrillic top-level domain name 'укр'.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] Already in December 2008 the *Company Center for Internet names of Ukraine* had announced the registration of domain names in two new top-level domains 'укр' and 'блог' (transliterated: *bloh*).
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The full set of required documents was submitted to ICANN on 26 November 2009 by the Ukrainian Network Information Center (UNIC).
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] Ukraine was one of the first countries that applied for the creation of domains in their native writing system, following Russia, Egypt and China.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The domain was expected to be available in the first half of 2010 since assignment of top-level domain takes about a month.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] In November 2009 UNIC Director Yuriy Honcharuk expected the new domain to start operating on the Internet in February–March 2010.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] On 1 March 2011, ICANN announced that the .укр domain had passed string evaluation, the step before delegation.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] .укр was approved by the ICANN Board on 28 February 2013.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The zone was added to the root servers on 19 March 2013.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The very first two domains were тест.укр (xn--e1aybc.xn--j1amh) and уміц.укр (xn--l1ank7d.xn--j1amh).
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] In Ukrainian "тест" stands for "test", and "уміц" stands for "Український Мережевий Інформаційний Центр", Ukrainian Network Informational Centre.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] According to UNIC Director Honcharuk, registration of .укр domain names could begin in the summer of 2013.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] Registration is allowed both in Russian and in Ukrainian.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The .укр registration of domains of Ukrainian government agencies in the Ukrainian language began on 22 August 2013.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] On 21 August 2013 the first such site got active — президент.укр (president.ukr).
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] Before the end of 2013, many sites were active.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] In June 2008 President Oleksandr Olshansky of the Ukrainian Internet company *Internet Invest* considered it unlikely that .укр would be assigned by ICANN.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] According to Olshansky the existing rules for non-Latin domain names stipulate that at least one letter should differ in the shape from the corresponding Latin character.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] The country name Україна (Ukraine) does not contain any letter whose shape does not exist in any Latin language.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] In November 2009 UNIC Director Yuriy Honcharuk had stated there were no technical issues preventing the assignment of this Cyrillic domain.
[src:cyrillic-script/укр] Latin ccTLDs contain two letters, whereas .укр contains three, which makes it recognizably distinct, especially with the lack of any such suffix as ".ykp".
[src:cyrillic-script/қаз] The .қаз domain exists as a symbol of national identity, but its popularity remains low compared to the Latin .kz and international domains.
[src:cyrillic-script/қаз] The main reasons are technical inconveniences and users' habit of using Latin addresses.
[src:cyrillic-script/қаз] Some second-level domains have been reserved in a prioritized manner, such as президент.қаз ("prezident.qaz").
[src:cyrillic-script/қаз] Between May 1, 2012 to July 31, 2012, companies and trademark holders could apply for their names.
